2016 USA Presidential Campaign Finance Analysis

by Rubens Mny

Abstract

The purpose of this analysis is to understand from where the 2016 US Presidential Elections contributions are coming, which are the most common characteristics of the average contributors profile, which candidate receives the highest amount of contributions and the amount received by party and state, so the Parties could drive their efforts based on data and information instead of other methods.

Introduction

The United States of Americas Presidential Election is the most important election among all nations.

Two interesting facts about US Presidential Elections:

  1. US has a dual party Democracy, although there are other parties that are part of it
  2. The campaigns are mostly privately funded but public financing is available as well

Source: Wikipedia on Campaign Finance in the United States

This analysis will be focused on financial information disclosed by each presidential candidate who has reported at least $100,000 in contributions from individuals other than the candidate.

This dataset is provided by the United States Federal Election Commission (FEC), and it includes data for all individual contributions reported on Form 3P Line 17A, refunds to individuals reported on Form 3P Line 28A and transfers from authorized committees reported on Form 3P Line 18, together with geographical data, so it is possible to dive into details like donation by City and ZIP Code.

Dataset source: Federal Election Commission - 2016 Presidential Campaign Finance

The main attributes of this dataset are: Candidate Name, Contributor City, Contributor State and Receipt Amount.

Besides the Candidates Name, the Contributor City and State are important to identify which region of the Country contributes (US$) most, so campaigns could be handled differently based on this fact.

Other attributes that might help to identify patterns or uncommon distributions are Form Type and Receipt Date.
The Form Type column indicates what schedule and line number the reporting committee reported a specific transaction:

- SA17A: Form 3P Schedule A Line 17A > Individual contributions
- SA18: Form 3P Schedule A Line 18 > Transfers from authorized committees
- SB28A: Form 3P Schedule B Line 28A > Refunds to individuals

Still regarding this dataset, three new variables were created:

Univariate Analysis

The univariate analysis helps to understand some basic relations between variables. And the dataset.
The main question was if there could be a trend or something that could be significative for the Parties to understand what could influence an election: gender, state, amount of contributions, type of contributions, etc.
This analysis demonstrated that:

  • Hillary clinton was the first in received contribution amount, more than three times than Donald Trump, the elected candidate
  • Bernie Sanders and Donald Trump were the second and third candidates, respectively, with more received contributions
  • Jeb Bush, Ted Cruz and Marco Rubio complete the list of Top 6 received contributions. Other candidates received some as well, but the amounts were not so expressive
  • Contributions from individuals really play a major role in US elections. Considering just the count of contributions, there were more than 6 millions coming from individuals agains 1.5 million coming from transfers from committees. The plot Count of contributions > by type of contribution (Form Type) demonstrates this fact

    Regarding Parties:

  • Democrats received most of the contributions (5+ million), when compared to the Republicans (1.6+ million).
  • Green and Libertarian Parties received a small number of contributions, and Independent candidate just a few ones.
  • California was the state with the highest number of contributions, with almost 1.5 million individual contributions. Then New York comes next, with 700k individual contributions, followed by Texas (600k) and Florida (400k).
    The univariate analysis can help, but they are not enough to identify the relationship among other variables.

Bivariate Analysis Section

Contribution by State: there are some outliers (i.e.individual contributions above USD 1 million), but when considering contributions below USD 25,000, the mean and median become clearer: 

##      Min.   1st Qu.    Median      Mean   3rd Qu.      Max. 
##       0.8     160.0     800.0   16927.6    4888.0 2963744.3

New York was the second State with more contributions (count), but when considering total USD, it became the first city from the TOP 20, followed by Washington, San Francisco, Los Angeles and Houston.
The mean and median are relatively low due to legal limits for individual contributions.
Individual contributions, even in smaller amounts, proved to be the major player when considering totals. The Form Type (contribution by Type) SA17A is related to contribution by individuals, while SA18 means transfer from committees.
So, in US elections, individual contributions really play an important role in the campaign, more than committees.
When considering total (USD) contributions destined to candidates, Hillary Clinton was the preferred, followed by Donald Trump and Bernie Sanders.
Ted Cruz received a lot of individual contributions, but hes got approximately half of what Bernie Sanders campaign received.

Multivariate Analysis

As previously stated, Hillary Clinton was the candidate whom received most of the contributions (USD), followed by Donald Trump and Bernie Sanders.
Individual contributors confirmed to be the major players in US elections campaign financing. In this aspect, they were the main responsibles for 69% of total contributions, against 31% coming from transfers from committees.
The second plot demonstrates it, by comparing total contributions by type and state.
The expection in this case goes to New York, the state with the highest total contributions, with 70% from it coming from the committees instead of individual contributors. That was the only exception between all states.
The third plot was meant to demonstrate if the candidate gender would be important for an election, but it could not be considered an important variable, since the contribution amount did not show an increase or decrease because of that.
By using data from previous election, this variable might provide a different perspective.
Total contributions by Party and State: disconsidering Green, Libertarian and Independent Parties (the ones which received a really small amount of contributions - 2% from total), the Democrates were the destination of 54% of total contributions, followed by Replublicans, with 44% of the total.
Texas, Ohio, Oklahoma, South Carolina, Tennessee, Louisiana and Florida were the states where Republicans received more contributions than Democrats. In all other states, the Democrats were the destination of the majority of contributions.

Final plots and summary

First plot

Contribution increase over time

First plot description

The first plot demonstrates a negatively-skewed distribution.
It shows the increase of contributions along the time, and the closer it gets to the election, the higher the contribution gets, and even after this event, still some contributions are made.
The months with the highest contribution were September and October, 2016.
By November 2016 (election date was November 8), the contribution total was reduced by approximately 60%, and it went almost to zero by December.
But it was interesting to realize that even after the election, some contributions were made.
The contributions were increasing moderately month-by-month, with some peaks in June, September and December, 2015, with a big increase by February 2016, when the Debates got intensified.
After the drop-out of some candidates (from February until May) the contribution amount decreased until May 2016, increasing in big jumps until Election Date.
A really good guideline for the 2016 US elections can be found here.
Source: The Guardian > How we got here: a complete timeline of 2016s historic US election

Second plot


Contribution increase over time, by candidate

Second plot description

At the very beggining of the Campaign, back to March 2015, the amount of contributions were relatively small, when compared to the next months.
The candidate Hillary Clinton always was one of the preferred by the contributors, together with Marco Rubio, Rand Paul and Ted Cruz. Al the others, including the winner - Donald Trump - received some contributions as well, but nothing that could be considered significative.
By January 2016, with the intensification of the Debates, the contributors decided for mostly five candidates: Bush, Clinton, Cruz, Rubio and Sanders. The others still received some contributions, but not in a significative amount.
The winner - Donald Trump - started to receive signicant contributions by June, 2016, but almost 75% less than the stronger candidate at that time - Hillary Clinton.
From this month on, the contributions started to strongly increase, and after Obamas speech endorsing Clinton (by June), her campaing started to receive more and more contributions, reaching more than USD 100 Million by October 2016, one month before the Election.
Bernie Sanders also endorsed Clinton by July 2016, and then the contributions got directed to two candidates: Clinton and Trump.
The closer to Election Day it gets, the higher the contribution amount.
Also, this is a negatively-skewed distribution.

Third plot


Total contribution by State and Party

Third plot description

This plot demonstrates that Georgia, Alabama, Florida, Texas and South Carolina States the Republican Party received more contributions than the Democrats.
In all other States, the Democrats received the highest amounts, with special attention to California, New York, DC, Louisiana and Massachussets, where the Republicans received at least 70% less than the Democrats.
As a summary, the Democrats Party received the highest contribution amount, followed by the Republicans Party.
Green, Independent and Libertarian Parties almost did not appear in the plot.
The interesting fact is that in no State there is an unique preference. It was always about Democrats and Republicans. And in some (rare) times, others.

Reflection

This was a very interesting dataset to work with, due to its importance and for the chance to find interesting insights on it. And a pleasure to see the results as well.
Despite all these facts, it took me some time to go deep into the dataset, and understand that the data was organized by the Federal Election Commission, but there were missing values in receipt amounts, ZIP codes had incomplete data, like the contributors occupation and so on, but overall data was ok.
This is an imbalanced dataset, just like almost all other datasets we will find in ERPs, census, and financial data. So, in my opinion, finding some datasets like Iris, Cars and FlightData with almost none (or zero) missing fields or invalid data are not what we will find in our regular projects.
For me, it was a challenge to work with R, since I got used to Python and Jupyter Notebook, but after all the initial difficulties, I found it to be easier and faster to work with, and I am taking this experience to the company that I work for.
There are a lot of opportunities laying around to work with data: sensors, census, economics, trucks and cars engine data and corporate data (licensed to use, naturally), just to mention a few.
About the plots: the course gave me a good understanding about which one to use and why I should use one instead of another, depending on the data. And the audience.
GGPlot, GGally and others took me a lot of time to understand, and I spent a lot of it trying to adjust visualization, legend and related visuals, but after that, it was great to realize the versatility of these packages, and plots are not so difficult to produce.
The dataset did not take too much time in the EDA phase, but the plots and HTML formatting took much more than I expected. Which is ok for the first R project.
It was required, for correlation tests, to change categorical data into numerical, but just for some analysis. The kind of this dataset can run just a few correlation tests, but with more data, a more accurate correlation can be calculated.
I will do it again next year with the 2020 Election data, so I can compare the datasets for any new variables and contributors accuracy, and use this study to go deeper into other facts that could identify trends or other aspects that could affect the results.
